🟦 Methodology of the Minute: The Smallest Complete Unit

Legal disputes often fail because of narrative drift.

Too many facts.

Too many emotions.

Too many issues mixed together too early.

LCES responds with the Smallest Complete Unit — SCU.

An SCU is the smallest amount of information needed to perform one coherent legal task without confusion, assumption, or drift.

🔹 A complete SCU contains:

- 📌 Issue — the precise legal or procedural question

• 📂 Facts — the concrete factual anchors tied to that issue

• 🎯 Objective — the specific output or action required

Example:

- Issue: Did the order halt the action?

• Facts: Stay entered July 24; deposition proceeded anyway

• Objective: Draft a preservation notice

🧩 The SCU logic:

A task is not ready until issue, facts, and objective connect.

If one is missing, the system should not guess.

It should escalate.

🟨 Why SCUs matter

The SCU method helps prevent:

- Narrative overload

• Panic-driven overfiling

• Unsupported assumptions

• Procedural confusion

• Hidden waiver risks

• Remedy-trigger blindness

Instead of treating the case as one large blob of information, LCES breaks the matter into reviewable units.

Each SCU stays narrow enough to execute and specific enough to inspect.

🛡️ The Escalation Rule

If the input is incomplete or ambiguous, LCES does not proceed blindly.

It asks for the missing element.

Because a defensible legal workflow cannot be built on guesswork.

⚖️ The SCU is where procedural engineering begins:

Small enough to act.

Complete enough to review.

Structured enough to preserve.

